        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>This is a Band 6 continuum observation in full polarization and thus uses the
widest possible bandwidths to maximize sensitivity. The requested 
RMS is 15 microJy/beam. We have estimated 
the peak flux in Stokes I as conservatively as possible to be 80 mJy/beam.
Assuming a 1% fractional polarization, this gives us a
polarized flux 800 microJy/beam and an SNR of about 53 at this peak position. However, we 
are proposing to be able to map the polarization structure down to 
the 10% level of the Stokes  I or total intensity. Near the outer edges, 
the fractional polarization is expected to be higher due to less issues with 
beam averaging. If we assume 3% polarization, the polarized flux density at the
10% contour will be 240 microJy/beam. At this contour level, 
the expected polarization SNR will be down to about 15. This constrains the 
polarization angle (relative measurement) to approximately 2 degrees.  
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We want the maximum available bandwidth for full polarization observations. Since 
this is a continuum polarization observation, the spectral setup need not be specified 
and is chosen by default (Table A-6 on page 29 of the Proposer's guide). In Band 6, 
SPW1, SPW2, SPW3, and SPW4 are set to be 224.0, 226.0, 240.0, and 242.0 GHz respectively 
with LO1 set to be 233.0 GHz. Each of the above spectral windows has a bandwidth of 
1.875 GHz.  </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The goal is to map the magnetic field structure in the disk around 
IRAS 16293B with an angular resolution of 0.2 arcseconds. This resolution 
will be considerably higher than our previous SMA observations which had 
a resolution of 0.6 arcseconds. We have selected Band 6 instead of Band 7 
to conduct the observations for the primary reason that both IRAS 16293 B 
and A will be within a field which is one-third the size of the primary beam 
at this frequency. The primary beam sizes and the field are shown in Figure 1
of the scientific justification.  

This disk has a geometry that is almost face on and this object is  therefore
an ideal candidate to study the field structure. The source size is 
approximately 1 arcsecond. With a resolution of 0.2 arcseconds, there will
be of order 100 independent pixels (or resolution elements) assuming a 
maximum recoverable size of 2.0 arcsec. There is 
expected to be an azimuthal variation in the polarization angle (See 
Figure 1 of scientific justification).  Any asymmetry in the structure
can therefore be mapped with sufficient resolution and fidelity.

The pointing center is in between source A and B, a little closer to B.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
